Data Driven Analysis of Player Performance

Project Report for STAT 303-1 Fall 2025

Author

Javier Hernandez

Published

December 9, 2025

Abstract
This project examines the key factors that influence a players rating, performance across age groups, variation in player quality, and recommendations on which players to but. The analysis identifies the technical and mental characteristics most strongly correlated with player rating and value, including interception, composure, ball control, and short and long passing. Overall, these findings give insights in how teams can be more effective in recruiting, scouting, and developing players by focusing on attributes depending on a players age range. The only issue is the dataset is outdated meaning some new players are not in the dataset as well as current players rating may not be up to date.

Imputing this may just affect the data and give false values for the data that we have.

In the numerical variables, there are no outliers, as many of the numbers fall within a certain range. Most variables are from 1-100 or 1-5. Meaning that there canât be any values that are outside of that range. This is helpful, as these evaluation metrics show us that there arenât any incorrect values or zero weight in the variables that were used for analysis.

We used a different number of categories and variables. Most of the categorical variables have five different categories, as it is asking for some of the playersâ characteristics to be evaluated out of five. For example, one being poor and five being mastered.

c) Analysis 3

To understand how players performance change depending on their age, I analyzed the relationship between age and overall rating. I created age groups (Young Adults, Adults, Senior Adults, and Veterans), and compared the average technical and physical attributes across different age categories. This allowed me to observe both general trends and specific performance differences across age ranges.

I first plotted a line graph showing how a playerâs overall rating changes with age. This reveals how players develop, peak, and eventually decline as they get older.

The line plot shows the performance curve that:
  • Ratings increase steadily from ages 17-24 as players develop both physically and mentally.
  • Between the ages of 25-33, players hit their optimal/peak performance window, showing the highest overall ratings.
  • Once a player reaches the age of 35, there is a gradual decline, and becomes even more noticeable after the age of 40.
This closely aligns with tht typical player development, where athletes hit there peak in their mid-to-late 20s and then gradually decrease as physical attributes are not what they used to be.
To explore how players within the same age group differ, I used the bins for age ranges I had created and plotted the distribution of rating within each group.
The box plot compares the spread of overall rating across the four age groups.
  • Young adults (17-20) show a wide spread, indicating variability. Some players are still developing while others are considered to be early bloomers.
  • Adults (21-28) also has a wide spread with many outliers being high performers and some underperforming compared to the rest of the age group.
  • Senior Adults (29-37) has the highest median ratings, however there does seem to be some variability possibly because players are starting to decline in the overall rating.
  • Veterans (38+) shows a clear drop in median rating compared to Senior adults this is due to having only a few exceptional players. As well as not having as many players as the rest of the age group. Meaning these few players boost up the median and mean of the age group.

This plot makes it clear that a players prime occurs in the senior adult age bracket. While young adult and adults are steadily increasing slowly with there performance and reaching optimal performance.

To understand why players peel at certain ages, I analyzed the average values for key technical and physical attributes across age groups. Including

  • Acceleration
  • Sprint Speed
  • Dribbling
  • Ball Control
  • Finishing
  • Short Passing
  • Stamina
  • Strength

I then visualized these using a radar chart for comparing the four age categories. This radar chart reveals how physical and technical abilities evolve with age.

Young Adults (17-20) have a strong acceleration and sprint speed. They compare lower in finishing and decision making attrbiuted to the ongoing development and lack of experience.

Adults (21-28) have the highest score in most technical and physical attributes. This is because this is considered the peak performance of a player, dominating in ball control, dribbling, short passing, and stamina.

Senior Adults (29-37) still maintain strong technical ability. However, we start seeing a small decline in acceleration and sprint speed. Strength improves slightly due to the experience and conditioning of the player.

Veterans (35+) experience significant decline in speed, dribbling, and finishing. Short passing and strength remain pretty stable. Finally their performance become more specialized rather then being well rounded like the Adults or some Senior Adults.

This visual clearly shows the transition from physically explosive players (Young Adults), technical dominant player (Adults), and more tactically experienced players (Veterans).

Across the visuals the performance trend is clear. Players improve from ages 17-20 as they develop more technically, physically, and they start to gain experience. The peak performance occurs between ages 21-28, players abilities start to peak. After the age of 30, physical decline begins, but technical attributes still remain stable. However, for player over the age of 35 although they retain strength and passing ability they lose most pace-driven attributes.

d) Analysis 4

The dataset contains players from over 160 different nations, showing a very diverse pool in the dataset. However, many of these nations only have a couple of players. So I decided to filter by the amount of players to help with consistency.

After grouping by nationality and calculating te mean overall rating for each the countries players, I selected the top 10 nations with the highest average player ratings that had at least 20 players.

This bar char displays the countries with the highest player ratings:

  • Countries like Portugal, Brazil, and Uruguay appear at the top reflecting their strong player development systems.
  • These countries not only produce elite players and do so consistently but also create many quality players.
  • This plot highlight that European football nations generally dominate in producing high-quality players compared to other nations.

Next I examined the distribution of player ratings within the top 10 countries to understand how consistent their player development is. Some nations may have a couple of superstars that bring up the average, while other countries may be more balanced.

The boxplot shows the spread such as the minimum, median, maximum, and quartiles of players rating for each country.

Countries like Egypt, Morocco, and Peru show tight distributions, meaning their talent levels are consistent, have few extreme outliers that may skew the data. Nations like Uruguay, Brazil, and Portugal show a much wider spread meaning that they produce elite players and low rated players. We see that a high average rating does not always mean consistent quality.

Each point in this scatter plot represents a nationality, showing its average player ration on the x-axis and the rating variability (standard deviation) on the y-axis.

On the bottom-right quadrant(high rating and low variability) there are countries like Peru, Egypt, and Cape Verde. These countries produce strong and consistent players, this is the ideal combination when looking at an overall rating.

The top-right quadrant (high rating and high variability) we see countries like Brazil, Uruguay, and Portugal. Producing elite starts but also more variance in talent. They are known for producing world class players. For brazil; Neymar, Ronaldinho, Ronaldo. For Portugal; Ronaldo, Figo, and Bruno Fernandes.

the Top-left quadrant(low rating and high variability) countries like Serbia, Ukraine, and Morocco does not develop great players and are generally weaker in overall rating.

Overall the plot shows that most European football nations combine both high talent and consistent, while some south american nations can produce a wider range of player quality.

b) Recommendation 2

When Recruiting a player some of the key in game characteristics that one should be focusing on is reactions, composure, potential, ball control, dribbling, short passing, and international reputation (depending if they do play for their nation).

The three most in game characteristics to focus on is composure, as this can tell a lot about a player. How well are they off the ball on the ball, do they lose the ball quickly, what exactly do they do with the ball, how do they react to certain different situations.

Dribbling is also a key component whether that is as a defender or as an attacker. As this can can help in determining how comfortable they are with the ball, how well they can lose there marker, making sure they donât lose the ball in dangerous areas, and knowing when is the time and place to take another player on a one-vs-one.

Finally ball control, can tell a lot about a players performance and how well they are able handle themselves in tight situations. When getting pressed from an opposition or when controlling a ball from a teammate. This is important as having a player that doesnât lose the ball and is comfortable in keeping and maintaining the ball is very important.

These are just some components to look out for when scouting a player to the team. Some things to take into consideration is how well will they adapt to the coaching style. The type of condition you want a player to be in, whether that is a little older but with more experience or a young player that is showing talent and will need guidance. With a risk of the player not living up to their potential.

c) Recommendation 3

The results of the age-based performance analysis suggest that there are several important recommendations when it comes to recruiting payers, development, and squad planning. First thing is clubs should prioritize players in the 24-29 age range, as this group demonstrated the highest overall rating and the most complete in terms of football profiles. Investing in players at their athletic and technical peak reduces uncertainty and ensures a dependable core within the squad. Meanwhile, Young adults should be viewed as a long term investment, as there is still much risk that can be taken in them. Although these players are not yet in there peak performance, they exhibit strong growth potential, meaning clubs can acquire these players at a relatively low cost and focus on developing these players emphasizing technical skills, tactical awareness, and physical conditioning.

This analysis also highlight the importance of managing and maintaining older players at a high level doing it in a strategic way. While senior and veteran players show declines in speed, dribbling, and other physical attributes, they are have strong mental qualities such as composure and positioning. As a result, clubs should change their trainings and match loads to avoid fatigue and injury. Additionally, age specific training programs should be implemented to reflect the differing needs of each group. Younger players would benefit from more intensive technical and tactical development, adults and older adults will require more maintenance to keep there peak level, and older players may benefit from reducing there workload and role in the team.

d) Recommendation 4

The nationality based analysis gave us a lot of insights that may help in enhancing scouting and player acquisition decisions. Countries such as Portugal, Uruguay, and Brazil consistently produce high rated players with high variability in performance, indicating that while these regions produce elite players they also have a wide performance range. Clubs targeting these regions should therefore be prepared for higher risk but also higher potential reward, especially when looking for future stars.

Standard deviation proved a valuable indicator of recruitment risk. Nations with lower variability offer greater stability, while nations with higher variability provide greater upside but require more rigorous scouting to differentiate the top talent from the performers who are inconsistent. Additionally many of the countries were underrepresented and many not taken into consideration due to not having many players. Finally, clubs seeking to improve there youth academies should look to the training models of high-performing nations. Being able to emphasize technical development, tactical education, and well structured academy system early on in a players age can help in replicating the consistent player quality seen in top producing countries.

8) Conclusion

Scouting for players can be a hard and long process it requires analyzing many aspects of the game and taking into consideration how well players will fit into the team, the structure, playing style, and how they will perform. Some of these things are hard to control and not in the coaching staffâs hands.

Scouters should look for a mix of technical skills such as a players touch, passing, and dribbling. As well as tactical intelligence (data that canât be shown in this data) such as their positioning, game sense, and decision making. An important aspect of the player is there physical ability (data that cannot be fully show here) such as there speed, stamina, and strength. Finally one last thing to take into consideration is there mental and character traits such as a players competitiveness, coachability, and teamwork. Focusing not just on a players raw talent but how well they perform under pressure is key as well as a players capacity to learn and fit into a team.

This is what Manchester United needs, although they may have some quality players they lack the depth, consistency, competitveness that they once had. Focusing on players not just with potential but how they fit into the team and what exactly they will be offering to the team is crucial. Having signed players that didnât give much as an impact as they thought from a one season wonder. Manchester United has the money to invest in high quality players it is just a matter of regaining the credibility and impact they once did as a team.

In conclusion, Manchester United need to focus on recruiting better player that will ultimately give them a better impact while also getting players that are in there peak that will give them many glorious years at the club.
